<DIV1 TYPE="notes">
<HEAD>NOTES.</HEAD>
<P><HI>Book</HI> ii. <HI>Epi&s;t.</HI> 1.] The Poet always ri&s;es with his original; and very often, without. This whole Imitation is extremely noble and &s;ublime.</P>
<P>VER. 7. <HI>Edward and Henry, etc.] Romulus, et Liber Pater, etc.</HI> Horace very judiciou&s;ly prai&s;es Augu&s;tus for the colonies he founded, not for the victories he won; and therefore compares him, not to tho&s;e who de&s;olated, but to tho&s;e who civilized mankind. The imitation wants this grace: and, for a very ob|vious rea&s;on, could not aim at it.</P>
